===Glyph origin===
{{Han etym}}
{{Han compound|門|耳|c1=p|c2=s|t2=ear|ls=psc}}. Compare {{och-l|問}}.

===Etymology===
Schuessler derives this from {{inh|zh|sit-pro|*mnam|*mnəm|to smell}}, whence {{cog|bo|མནམ་པ||to smell of}}, {{cog|bo|སྣོམ་པ||to smell}}, {{cog|kac|manam|tr=mə³¹ nam⁵⁵|t=smell}}, {{cog|my|နမ်||to smell}}, {{cog|my|နံ||to stink}} ({{zh-ref|Schuessler, 2007}}). It is very phonetically difficult, requiring an inversion of ''n'' and ''m'' in Chinese (which Schuessler attributes to labial dissimilation or prefix-preemption) in addition to rejecting the Baxter-Sagart reconstruction with a ''*u'' in favour of reconstructing ''*ə'' instead (''*u'' and ''*ə'' are difficult to distinguish before ''*-n''). The reconstruction with ''*u'' is solidified by rhyming patterns in the ''{{w|Classic of Poetry}}'', making Schuessler's etymology impossible.

In almost all major Tibeto-Burman languages, this etymon means only "to smell". Schuessler explains the application of "to hear" in Chinese via various influences. He sees a parallel in Tibeto-Burman ''*na'' "ear ~ nose" and hence perhaps in Sino-Tibetan (see {{m|sit-pro|*r/g-na||ear}}). The Chinese stem may have converged with a Mon-Khmer etymon (cf. {{cog|mkh-mnc-pro|*smaaɲ''||to inquire}} ([[ibid.]]). Schuessler also notes {{cog|bo|མཉན་པ||to listen to; to hear}}, which he deems phonologically quite close to Chinese.

Pronunciation 2 ("be heard about; renowned; fame") is a derivation of pronunciation 1, with passive suffix ''*-s'' ([[ibid.]]).

{{och-l|問|to ask}} is the [[exoactive]] derivation of pronunciation 1 with suffix ''*-s'', literally "let (me) hear" ([[ibid.]]).

